04748nam a22006615i 9781487574949DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191987onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875749497 a10.3138/97814875749492doi  a(DE-B1597)536801  a(OCoLC)1129180176  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.61 aTracy, Clarence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Portrait of Richard Graves /cClarence Tracy. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology -- tCHAPTER ONE. Family -- tCHAPTER TWO. Childhood -- tCHAPTER THREE. Pembroke -- tCHAPTER FOUR. All Souls -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Gentleman and the Christian -- tCHAPTER SIX. Tissington -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Utrecia -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Lucy -- tCHAPTER NINE. The Clerical Calling -- tCHAPTER TEN. Home -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. School -- tCHAPTER TWELVE. Friends, Old and New -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN. Trifling -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN. The Novels -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN. The Sprightly Mr Graves -- tAbbreviations Appendixes Notes -- tAbbreviations -- tAPPENDIX A. Richard Graves's Publications -- tAPPENDIX B. A Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has been said that one of the finest achievements of the Church of England was the maintenance of one well-educated man in every English community. Such a man was Richard Graves. He is best remembered as the author of The Spiritual Quixote, and engaging comic novel written in the mid-eighteenth century. But this life was essentially that of a rural parson. In exploring that life, Clarence Tracy allows us a detailed view of rural English society of the period as well as an appreciation of Graves’s writing. As the second son of a family of landed gentry, Graves was raised with a well-defined sense of his position in society but no income with which to sustain it. He found his place as a fellow at All Souls College, Oxford, from which vantage point his future looked bright. But he fell in love with a young woman, Lucy Bartholomew, and secretly married for a few weeks before she before their first child. Marriage was forbidden to fellows of All Souls, and when Graves’s was discovered he lost his position. Eventually he found a living as rector of Claverton, near Bath, where he settled with Lucy and their five children. Happy in his marriage and generally content with his work, Graves stayed in Claverton for fifty years. Those who have read The Spiritual Quixote will recognize many familiar elements in Graves’s story. Tracy illustrates the close parallels between the novel and life, and discusses other aspects of Graves’s writing as well. Those who have not read his works will be tempted to do so after reading this biography and will certainly have a heightened understanding of rural life in eighteenth-century England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthors, Englishy18th centuryvBiography. 0aClergyzEnglandvBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757494940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487574949423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487574949.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PP